columns.text:
The Fisher equation calculated the real effective annual rate, so we can use those rates in our APR calculation. The number of compounds in a year is 12. 

By inputting the values into Eq.$(2)$, we can calculate the <b><span style="color: #4257B2">annual percentage rate (APR)</span></b> of our stock account:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{APR}_\text{ Stock}
&= \Bigg(\Big(1 + 0.0673\bigg)^{\dfrac{1}{12}} - 1\Bigg) \times 12 \\[25pt]
&= 6.530\%. \\[10pt]
\end{aligned}$$

And similarly, for the bond account:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{APR}_\text{ Stock}
&= \Bigg(\Big(1 + 0.02884\bigg)^{\dfrac{1}{12}} - 1\Bigg) \times 12 \\[25pt]
&= 2.846\% .\\[10pt]
\end{aligned}$$
